{"cursor":"33186","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"/water showing azeotropic behavior]]\n\nAn 'azeotrope' ( or ) is a mixture of two or more liquids in such a way that its\ncomponents cannot be altered by simple distillation. Moore,\nWalter J. Physical Chemistry, 3rd ed., Prentice-Hall 1962, pp. 140â142\nThis happens because, when an azeotrope is boiled, the vapor it produces has\nproportionate constituents as the original mixture.\n\nBecause their composition is unchanged by distillation, 'azeotropes' are\nalso called (especially in older texts) 'constant boiling mixtures'. The\nword azeotrope is derived from the Greek words Î¶Î­ÎµÎ¹Î½ (boil) and ÏÏÏÏÎ¿Ï\n(turning) combined with the prefix Î±- (no) to give the overall meaning, \"no\nchange on boiling\".\n\nAzeotropic mixtures of pairs of compounds have been documented. (See Azeotrope (data)). Many azeotropes of three or more\ncompounds are also known. {{Cite web\n  | last = Department of Chemical Engineering University of Alicante title =\n  | Numerical Determination of Distillation Boundaries for Multicomponent\n  | Homogeneous and Heterogeneous Azeotropic Systems url = http://www.aidic.it/escape20/webpapers/134Reyes-\n  | Labarta.pdf}}\n\n","linknr":455,"url":"Azeotrope","recorded":1362371859,"links":57,"instances":["chemistry","data","molecule","unit","chemistry","unit","poetry"],"pdf":["http://www.chemeng.ntnu.no/thesis/download/2000/hilmen/Thesis_Hilmen.pdf","http://www.chemeng.ntnu.no/thesis/download/2000/hilmen/Thesis_Hilmen.pdf","http://www.aidic.it/escape20/webpapers/134Reyes-Labarta.pdf","http://www.aidic.it/escape20/webpapers/134Reyes-Labarta.pdf","http://ts.nist.gov/MeasurementServices/ReferenceMaterials/upload/1828.pdf","http://ts.nist.gov/MeasurementServices/ReferenceMaterials/upload/1828.pdf"],"categories":["Thermodynamics","Phase transitions","Separation processes"],"headings":["Types","Homogeneous and heterogeneous azeotropes","Distillation of mixtures","Phase diagrams","He